{
  "ADUs": {
    "1": {
      "text": "Determinism is the thesis that our universe is deterministically predictable.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "Incompatibilism is the claim that determinism rules out our having free will.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "If determinism is true, then our acts are the consequences of the laws of nature and events in the remote past.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "But it is not up to us what went on before we were born, and neither is it up to us what the laws of nature are.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "Therefore, the consequences of these things (including our present acts) are not up to us.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "In what follows, I will exploit this argument to prove the opposite conclusion: determinism, if it is true, does not rule out free will.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "The problem of free will arises only if we make a controversial assumption logically independent of determinism, one that Van Inwagen (and many other incompatibilists) would deny, namely, that God does not exist.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "8": {
      "text": "If determinism is compatible with God's existence, it is compatible with free will.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "9": {
      "text": "Suppose, then, that determinism is true. And suppose too that a God exists who, as Van Inwagen puts it, 'is superior to and not a part of Nature (this enormous object that the natural sciences investigate)...'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "10": {
      "text": "Determinism does not require that God's actions be predictable on the basis of natural laws; hence it is compatible with the existence of such a being.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "11": {
      "text": "If God intervenes in history, stopping the sun at Jericho, raising the dead, it may still be true that every event in nature has a cause, either natural or supernatural.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "12": {
      "text": "But determinism is false in that case, for it is false that every event in nature is a consequence of the past and natural laws.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "13": {
      "text": "Nonetheless, if God exists in it, miracles are still possible.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "14": {
      "text": "Consequently, in a God-occupied deterministic universe nothing must happen as it does.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "15": {
      "text": "I submit that, with supernatural assistance, we can render laws false.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "16": {
      "text": "By enabling us to do this, God could give us the power to refrain from actions determined by the remote past and natural laws.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "17": {
      "text": "Determinism, therefore, does not logically preclude free will.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "18": {
      "text": "To sum up: Determinism does not preclude human freedom.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "19": {
      "text": "If it is compatible with God's existence, determinism is compatible with free will.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "20": {
      "text": "Naturalistic incompatibilism is false.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
